{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508859"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:09:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11356"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11356","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11356"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.34,0.05,0.16,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108980"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4001"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11356"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91350"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"476"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"2545"},{"type":"tags","id":"3983"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4005"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27012"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38735"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40393"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40676"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108980"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA three-year-old boy presents to his General Practitioner with a two-week history of fever, fatigue, and sore throat. His parent reports he has been increasingly irritable and has had reduced appetite. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. He attends daycare but his parent denies recent travel or known sick contacts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell with a pulse rate of 110/min, blood pressure 95/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.2\u00b0C. His chest is clear on auscultation. Exudates are present on both tonsils. Cervical lymphadenopathy is present bilaterally. There is fullness and mild tenderness in the left upper quadrant of his abdomen.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tests is most appropriate to facilitate a diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Full blood exam","Heterophile antibody (monospot) test","CMV serology (IgM \u0026 IgG)","EBV PCR","EBV serology (IgM \u0026 IgG)"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis three-year-old patient presents with a two-week history of fever, pharyngitis, and lymphadenopathy, which represents the classic triad of infectious mononucleosis. The prolonged fever duration and clinical findings strongly suggest Epstein-Barr virus infection, which is the most common cause of infectious mononucleosis in children. EBV testing is not performed routinely; however, indications for testing may include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFever lasting longer than two weeks (such as this case)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESevere clinical features\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen confirmation would alter management (such as stopping unnecessary antibiotic therapy)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPatients engaging in strenuous activity where the splenic rupture risk needs assessment\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEBV serology (IgM \u0026amp; IgG)\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate diagnostic test in this clinical scenario. IgM antibodies to EBV capsid antigen indicate acute infection and become detectable around symptom onset, while IgG antibodies indicate past infection and remain for life. This test has a sensitivity and specificity of 97% and 94% respectively, and provides clear differentiation between acute and past infection, making it particularly valuable in young children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFull blood exam\u003C/strong\u003E may show supportive findings such as lymphocytosis and atypical lymphocytes in up to 90% of EBV cases, but these findings are not specific for EBV infection and cannot definitively establish the diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHeterophile antibody test\u003C/strong\u003E (also known as the Monospot test) has significant limitations in this patient population. False negatives are common in children under four years of age and early in the illness, particularly within the first three weeks of symptoms. Given this patient\u0027s age and the two-week duration of symptoms, this test would be unreliable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECMV serology (IgM \u0026amp; IgG)\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if cytomegalovirus infection were suspected. While CMV is the second most common cause of infectious mononucleosis syndrome, EBV remains more common, particularly in this age group with the classic presentation described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEBV PCR\u003C/strong\u003E has excellent sensitivity and specificity (98% and 97%, respectively), but is primarily reserved for immunocompromised patients or specific clinical scenarios, such as post-transplant monitoring. It has no established role in diagnosing EBV infection in this case.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["EBV serology (IgM \u0026 IgG) is the most reliable test for diagnosing acute EBV infection in young patients with prolonged fever.","The heterophile antibody test has high false negative rates in children under 4 years and early in illness.","Diagnostic testing for EBV is indicated for prolonged fever \u003E2 weeks, severe features, or when confirmation would alter management."],"references":["Turabelisze, G., Infectious mononucleosis [Internet] bestpractice.bmj.com 2021 [cited 19 Sep 2021]. Available from https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/123/pdf/123/Infectious%20mononucleosis.pdf","Aronson, M., Auwaerter, P., Infectious mononucleosis [Internet] www.uptodate.com 2021 [cited 19 Sep 2021]. Available from https://www.uptodate.com/contents/infectious-mononucleosis","Electronic Therapeutic Guidelines. 2021. Epstein\u2013Barr virus (EBV) infection. [online] [Accessed 15 July 2025] Available at: https://tgldcdp-tg-org-au.ezproxy.flinders.edu.au/viewTopic?topicfile=epstein-barr-virus\u0026guidelineName=Antibiotic#toc_d1e47","De Paschale M, Clerici P. Serological diagnosis of Epstein-Barr virus infection: Problems and solutions. World J Virol. 2012 Feb 12;1(1):31-43. doi: 10.5501/wjv.v1.i1.31. PMID: 24175209; PMCID: PMC3782265. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24175209/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91350"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11356"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91350","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91350"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T13:43:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T13:44:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4001"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108980"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30